  "summary": "Upon arriving at Eustace Manor, Hercule Poirot receives a cold reception from Mrs. Olivia and her daughter, Jane, the latter of whom displays open hostility toward him. During dinner, Alistair Brent inquires about Helen Montgomery, but Mrs. Olivia claims Helen is resting after working in the garden. Later, Poirot overhears a private conversation in the ladies' lounge where Jane accuses her mother of neglecting Helen, while Mrs. Olivia dismisses Helen as a mere distant cousin and a burden to Uncle Alastair.\n\nAlistair Brent summons Poirot to his room to express his dissatisfaction with the official decision to halt the search for a woman named Mabel Sainsbury-Sil. Brent shares his suspicions regarding a bizarre case involving a dentist's suicide and a disfigured woman named Chapman. He suspects that a woman he encountered on the steps may have orchestrated a meeting to draw attention to him. Poirot suggests the woman might be dead and asks Brent if he recalls anything unusual during his dental appointment with Mr. Morley. Brent recalls seeing a blonde girl, an Irish dentist, and a restless young man in the waiting room, but noted nothing suspicious.\n\nPoirot identifies the young man as Howard Lick, a friend of Jane. He suggests to Brent that Mrs. Olivia brought Jane from America specifically to separate her from Lick, a relationship her mother disapproves of.",
